e":"Innes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   McInnis  , from Gaelic <b>Mag Aonghuis</b> ‘son of Aonghus’.","Scottish: habitational name from the barony of Innes in Urquhart (Morayshire), named from Gaelic <i>inis</i> ‘island’.","English: variant of   Ince  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Inniss","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  ."]},{"name":"Ince","meanings":["habitational name from Ince in Makerfield (Lancashire), Ince (Cheshire), or Ince Blundell (Lancashire). The placenames derive from Proto-Welsh <i>ïnïs</i> ‘island’.","possibly a post-medieval West Midlands variant of <b>Hints</b>, a habitational name from either of two places called Hints (Staffordshire, Shropshire). The placenames probably derive from Proto-Welsh <i>hïnt</i> ‘way, path’ + Middle English plural <i>-es</i>.","possibly a variant with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i> of <i>Inn</i>, from residence at an <i>inn</i> or <i>inns</i>, from Middle English <i>in</i> (singular) or <i>innes</i> (plural) ‘tavern, lodging(s), tenement(s)’. There seems also to have been some confusion with Scottish   Innes  ."]},{"name":"Inch","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  .","English: perhaps, at least in some cases, a variant of   Ince  .","English: variant of   Hinch  ."]},{"name":"McInnis","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aonghuis</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Aonghus</i> (see   Angus  ). See also   McInnes  , compare Irish   McGinnis  ."]},{"name":"Innis","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  .","English: variant of   Ince  ."]},{"name":"Inness","meanings":["Scottish (Durham and Northumberland): variant of   Innes  ."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander de Innes 4th of Innes - of that Ilk was born about 1200, his father, Walter de Innes III of Innes - of that Ilk, was 22 and his mother, Lady Walter de Innes, III, was -8. He married Lady Alexander Innes of Innes before 1220, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1260, in Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 61, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"Abt 1200–1260":"umbes 1200–1260","1200–1260":"1200–1260","–Female":"Surnud","1240–1290":"1240–1290","1240–1296":"1240–1296","1180–1240":"1180–1240","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","Abt 1240":"umbes 1240","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","before 1220":"enne 1220","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","about 1230":"umbes 1230","1180":"1180","1290":"1290","Innes, Morayshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Moray, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Morayshire, Scotland":"Elginshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"Abt 1200–1260":"noin 1200–1260","1200–1260":"1200–1260","–Female":"Kuollut","1240–1290":"1240–1290","1240–1296":"1240–1296","1180–1240":"1180–1240","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","Abt 1240":"noin 1240","Abt 1200":"noin 1200","before 1220":"ennen vuotta 1220","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","about 1230":"noin 1230","1180":"1180","1290":"1290","Innes, Morayshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Moray, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Scotland","Morayshire, Scotland":"Elginshire, Scotlan